text: Ok, I'll have to check this out, and it looks like Legendary should be the ones to handle every anime live-action movie, because I am stunned at how good the Pokemon look in live-action. In fact, doesnt WB have the film rights to Akira? Let Legendary handle that one, especially.  Lastly, it wouldve been better if Danny Devito voiced Detective Pikachu, but Ryan is a good 2nd choice, especially after Deadpool, which guarantees that this movie, which is not only a film based off an anime/manga, its based off a video game too. Rare good anime-based films are one thing, but good video game-based films are even more rare.   Seriously, at least live-action anime films are slowly getting good in recent years(for starters, the Bleach film is pretty good. It earned sequels), but I cant say the same for video-game based movies. The only 2 I can think of that are point to the games they're based on, are Hitman and Assassin's Creed. So, other than them, Detective Pikachu will be another, and, there's a live-action Sonic movie coming(which will probably have Sonic and the rest look like how Detective Pikachu looks).

text: My main problem with this movie is that jokes and references might go over the heads of non-Pokemon players. I, who has played Pokemon games since Crystal, understand that Jigglypuff puts people to sleep and draws on their faces, who Greninja is, and that Mr. Mime used Barrier to stop Pikachu from jumping on him. My Dad, who will probably want to watch this because he loves Ryan Renolds movies, is not going to get anything about it while I sit next to him shitting myself from the references.   On the other hand, if they do minimal references, then it'll just end up as another generic buddy cop movie where one partner happens to be an electric mouse, losing what their potential target audience is, Pokemon fans. Or else they end up spending large portions of the movie explaining stuff for non-Pokemon fans, taking away from the joke and dragging out the movie.   It's a double edged sword, and I hope that they pull it off well, because I REALLY want to see good Nintendo-based theatrical movies.

I'm very interested to know if there is anyone who read this comment able to ponder about my upcoming question; Why is it that in all of these exciting, up-beat and big-budget movies, such as the latest installment of 'Power Rangers', the latest installment of 'Pacific Rim', the latest installment of Star Wars, to name a few for reference, why is it that all of them heavily feature the main protagonist as a black with Nordic or Oriental beliefs and courage in these similar action-movies? It's strange to me that the black has all the on-screen-time needed to build a relationship with the audience. Who is this marketing toward and for what reason? Blacks make up near zero of the audience for these exciting and lively action-movies world-wide and/or in any individual country. I've yet to see a reason other than a forced inaccuracy toward/against the audience who pay to watch the movie. I ask, for my own ease-of-mind, as to why, on a big-budget American made-movie, is there not a quick-witted, lively, energetic, and honest Vietnamese to play the lead roll with well-executed dialogue? Or perhaps a Filipino, or frankly, anyone who make up the audience of the people who pay to watch it? If anyone believes that world-wide the viewer-number is high with negative criticism for all of the example movies simply because lots of people exist in the world, imagine the viewer-number if the movie wasn't retarded or ironic.

text: So... Pokemon has officially joined A&TC, the Smurfs, and many others to make a live-action film... Great... No thank you. You can tell by this point that, in terms of movies and the actual anime, Pokemon has run out of ideas. From simply remaking episodes and movies, to, now, this... When will this all end already? It should have died years ago. Oh, and one more note... For anyone that says that the reason Ash is still the main character after all these years is because "He's a good role model for young audiences..." "He lives and looks to achieve his own dreams..." Etc., etc., etc... Here's the living proof why Ash is still there... PIKACHU, even though other Pokemon like Eevee, Lucario, Mewtwo, and others have become just as popular... The anime keeps proving that Pikachu is the sole reason for its continuation... Heck, the main characters in Yu-gi-oh are better role models than Ash, in my opinion. At least... They actually accomplished much and didn't have the animators constantly trying to kill them off in almost every way  possible.

text: I'm skeptical to say the very least. This may sound cringey and overly dramatic to some people, but. As a Pokemon fan who grew up with Pokemon since its beginnings...I have high standards as there are many well-rooted emotions attached to this franchise. Pokemon has been a part of my life. It was my escape, it was something I was isolated for and defensive of as a kid. Which isn't necessarily a bad thing. Anything different, like Pokemon, is going to isolate people to an extent. That's only touching the surface of how much Pokemon impacted my life. Granted, I did go through the phase of wishing Pokemon was more mainstream, that it could be adapted into a live action film.   But I was young. As I grew older I obviously began to appreciate Pokemon for what it is. Pokemon is not purely innocent, but the innocent, happy-go-lucky feel is part of what makes Pokemon, Pokemon. It's not your run of the mill, typical dark Hollywood action comedy. The lack of the Pokemon feel and the idea of people potentially associating Pokemon with this movie alone, bothers me. I want to be open-minded, but I'll be honest. I really can't stomach the idea of Pikachu beng voiced by Deadpool like something resembling Ted of all things. No matter how hard I try to like it, it goes back to sounding like a complete nightmare every time. Which has led me to this rant in the hopes that others understand the emotions behind this franchise, why some people are sounding "harsh" towards this movie. It just looks like someone made the rash decision of, "This is not good enough. It needs to be what everything else is."  Don't get me wrong, I understand why they went with the route that they did. Because what Pokemon actually IS, is probably not all that appealing for a mainstream audience. But that's why I eventually decided a live action movie is probably a bad idea to begin with. Because Pokemon is a unique series, it's not for everyone. If you were to truly make a series for *everyone*, it becomes diluted and loses its originality. I'm not against change in the sense of limiting something entirely, I'm only against it to the extent that it loses its original, special touch that made it successful and what it means to so many fans today. I get and accept the need for change, change is often crucial in order to keep things moving. That's how life works. But change can backfire when it's unnecessary and takes away the original foundations. Positive change builds upon what was already successful, it does not take away and restart the entire process.  This isn't about gatekeeping. I approve of anything that brings more fans into the series. But only for the "right reasons," for what Pokemon is and not for what it thinks it needs to be in order to appeal to every single person.

text: Already looks better than the past few video game based movies we've recently gotten. And if this actually turns out to be really good, it could open the door for a live action Pokemon film based on Ash's adventures. I was scared they'd all have ugly Bay TMNT redesigns, but thankfully most of them have a realistic touch while still retaining their original look and charm. I'm personally looking forward to it, even though I know the fight scene with Charizard is gonna be a quick 5 minutes that we'll all wish we could have gotten more of. They could have played it safe and just ripped the designs from the games and not bother giving them a realistic touch, to which everyone would be complaining about how they don't have a realistic look. Plus the noir feel is a nice touch with the city lighting, and Pokemon are seen and integrated in most of the scenes, they could have just lazily shot most of this in a random city and slapped Pikachu in there and occassionally another Pokemon. But they took the time to put a hell of a lot of detail/references in the backgrounds and overall environment. It feels like a live action Pokemon world, not a generic Hop or Garfield cgi romp. I see effort here, and I'm looking forward to the end result come next year.

text: I'm gonna be honest. I'm not easily convinced by these type of things. But the trailer does show that it wants to integrate half of the charm of Pok√©mon and half of a "what if we made it real-life"? It was only natural they did this. CGI is now at a point where it's not as jarring as before. The premise is clearly a safe choice. They didn't go with the usual "gotta catch em all" thing but still have the "I want to become a champion" hidden in there, used to give the MC some kind of interesting backstory to build up on while the main focus is the detective pikachu.  I thought for sure the CGI was gonna look either bland or bad but it is not bad at all. They could've easily done the Mr. Mime scene way darker or edgier but instead gave us a more funnier approach (which is the main thing in the Detective Pikachu game where they talk about crimes and successfully sugarcoat it with the charms of pok√©mon).  Idk, I'll still give it time to see if it is worth a watch but I am interested. It does not look Pok√©mon visually but it does feel Pok√©mon in its theme.

text: Recipe for beautiful yummy Pikachu pancakes:     INGREDIENTS  1/2 cups yellow food coloring  2 cups all-purpose flour  1 1/2 tablespoons extra-fine granulated sugar  Pinch of salt  1 egg  2 egg yolks  2 1/2 cups milk  2 tablespoons vegetable oil, divided  1/2 stick (1/4) cup unsalted butter  Granulated sugar, lemons, and oranges for garnish  PREPARATION  1. In a large mixing bowl, whisk together the flour, sugar, food colouring and salt. Add the egg and egg yolks, followed by the milk and 1 tablespoon of the vegetable oil. Continue whisking until there are no lumps. In a separate small saucepan, melt the butter until it is golden brown, and whisk it into the pancake mix. Leave the batter to rest for about 15 minutes.  2. Heat an 8-inch frying pan until hot, and add the remaining 1 tablespoon vegetable oil, tilting the pan to spread the oil across the bottom. When the oil starts to smoke, pour the excess into a small bowl for later use. Return the pan to the heat. You now have a sheer coating of oil remaining on the pan.  3. Pour 2 tablespoons of the batter into the pancake pan, tilting the pan to coat the bottom evenly. Cook until the underside of the pancake is golden brown, and then, using a spatula turn it over and cook the other side. Turn the pancake out onto an upturned dinner plate. Repeat until there is no more batter, using a bit of the reserved oil if the pan appears to be dry, or if the pancakes begin to stick. Continue to stack pancakes on top of each other on your dinner plate.  4. When finished, served the pancakes straightaway with the sugar for sprinkling and the lemon and orange wedges on the side for squeezing on the pancakes.  5. If you want to make the pancakes in advance, lightly butter an ovenproof tray, and sprinkle each pancake with sugar after you finish cooking it. Fold the pancakes in half and then half again, arranging them all neatly on the tray. Cover the tray with foil and bake at 350 degrees for about 15 minutes. Serve with the lemon and orange wedges. ------------- Edit:  I didn't think this would get so many thums up, thank you! text: Okay. Not a fan of the Pokemon franchise and this does NOT look like the kinda movie to change that. The premise seems weird in a bad way and all the Pokemon look exactly like the cartoons just with more detailed textures, still, though that isn't inherently a bad thing, it is good to keep the designs source material accurate, but this is one of those times when they're too accurate. They look so unrealistic that they break the illusion completely, the cgi isn't all that great to boot. All of that on top of Ryan Reynolds getting cast for Pikachu, I mean I like Ryan, he's a fantastic actor and super funny, but it's no secret that he has made some stupid career choices and this'll be one of 'em. Seriously, his voice doesn't match the face at all, as if the who-framed-roger-rabbit looking cgi Pokemon aren't illusion breaking enough then that certainly is. Hate to be a buzz-kill, especially in regards to a video game movie, but don't get your hopes up.

text: His voice fits so well since we love subverted expectations.  Ryan Reynolds for cute ol' fuzzy pikachu is a great fit. Having Chris Pratt would be good but it wouldn't subvert anything, you'd just get what you'd expect. Having Reynolds and his person charm as well as wit brings the very things that even this IP has t heard of.  I hope the story is decent because that's all it really needs to be. The other protagonist just needs to lead the narration well and not speak too much; Reynolds entertain the audience, let the hype not be too great, maybe even have a NOT OBVIOUS VILLIAN like the guy who was the Father's friend.  It would even be great for Justice to even be an Trainer on Accident but with the other casts members, it would be great for some basic pokemon battle narrative slipped in there as a part of the Pro. Pokemon Trainer profile.  It would also be great to just have that pokemon index thingagigger for pokemon threats or simply as a nod then maybe just call out conventional attacks idk.   I hope this movie doesn't take itself so seriously. It just needs to be decent not great for the influx of good live action anime to pour in. Actually above average would be amazing.   America as a whole doesn't *really* know what "anime" is as a genre so opening/ introducing it mainstream for major movies it indeed a start. I just hope this doesn't start an movie only cult following as opposed to what the movie is actually influenced by.   This comedic approach is good to eating the wider American populace in getting to know the general appeal. Now, i hope that it will further ease that transitio. Without majorly whitewashing the content for an American audience.

Mix in a little typical humor like Mr. Mime miming them to shove it as they play good cop and bad cop along with a substantial dash of predictable humor in fight scenes. The plot theme of this young mans father being a detective whom was killed on a case and his son trying to find out what happened while he makes friends with a cute fluffy creature that involuntarily, and unexpectedly they just end up with one another and end up becoming friends sense they seem to find value in their somewhat functioning ever so slightly abusive relationship as friends.  Definitely not wasting my money on this film as I don't like Pokemon as it is and these types of movies make me cringe whenever they attempt to adapt it to western audiences.  Pokemon fans I wish you luck and prosperity :D
